<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-452-833  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 452 833.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Healthcare  Oct 1990 v11 n10 p14(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Confronting 2000 and beyond: tomorrow's healthcare informationsystem. (Cover Story)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zinn, Tim K.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Healthcare information systems in the year 2000 will need toaddress functional needs of patients and staff to insure thatcompeting hospitals provide quality managed care to patients.andO;Other hospitals, physicians, payors, consumers and the governmentare, and will continue to be, concerned with hospital performanceindicators; clinical information systems must be capable offurnishing these indicators efficiently, both to improve overallorganization, and to promote a focus on providing qualityhealthcare.andP;  Healthcare information systems of the future willneed to consolidate myriad medical data into one digital orautomated computerized format.andP;  Further, today's financial-basedhospital information systems will no longer be adequate to meet ahospital's needs; a shift from financial to clinical informationsystems will be required.andP;  Several other industry-specific needsare discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Hospital Information SystemsHealth CareCompetitionFuture TechnologiesQuantitative Methods.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Summary of healthcare information systems trends. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>